Analyze the following PlantUML use case model and detect if it contains any antipatterns.
Base your analysis solely on the model provided. Do not use any outside knowledge.


PlantUML Model:
@startuml
' Version 1 – contains Functional Decomposition: Using the include relationship

actor "Editor" as Editor
actor "Reader" as Reader
actor "Journalist" as Journalist

rectangle "News Publishing System" {
  usecase "Write Article" as UC1
  usecase "Publish Article" as UC2
  usecase "Validate Content" as UC3
  usecase "Browse Articles" as UC4
  usecase "Search Articles" as UC5
  usecase "Manage Categories" as UC6
}

Journalist --> UC1
Editor --> UC2
UC2 ..> UC3 : <<include>>
Reader --> UC4
Reader --> UC5
Editor --> UC6
@enduml


Answer:
Antipattern Detected: Functional Decomposition: Using the include relationship

   Constructs Involved: Publish Article (base use case), Validate Content (inclusion use case), <<include>> from "Publish Article" to "Validate Content"
   Explanation: "Validate Content" is an inclusion use case that is included by only one use case ("Publish Article"). It is not associated with any actor directly — no actor has an association to it. It does not include or extend any other use case, is not extended by any use case, and is neither a generalization nor a specialization. "Validate Content" does not represent a complete, standalone service offering an observable result to any user; it is merely a decomposed step of the "Publish Article" process. This constitutes the Functional Decomposition antipattern via the include relationship.
